  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12699">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following and discuss with your counselor:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12699 mb-requirement-id-12700">
        (a) Obtain safety data sheets (SDS) for sucrose (sugar), isopropyl
        alcohol (rubbing alcohol), and a waterproofing spray. Compare their
        properties and potential hazard(s), including handling and disposal
        guidelines and toxicity information. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_yWF-w3CwmU" target="_blank"
          >Safety Data Sheets Training (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12699 mb-requirement-id-12701">
        (b) What types of personal protective equipment (PPE) are recommended
        for each, and why? How does the recommended PPE change with toxicity and
        route of exposure? <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/i1D6zpSw_6Q?si=ktvcHSrfviHvAK2z"
          target="_blank"
          >How to Dress in the Lab and the Use of PPE (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12699 mb-requirement-id-12702">
        (c) Review the pictograms in Section 2 of each SDS. What do they mean,
        and how do you see them used in your community? <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/x_TebXJET0Y?si=Lualg-CYIcshzBxE"
          target="_blank"
          >Safety Pictograms in SDS (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12699 mb-requirement-id-12703">
        (d) Discuss the safe storage of chemicals. How does the safe storage of
        chemicals apply to your home, school, community, and the environment?
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/4GUSQj-xOBY?si=CI7Brkhm2NkXs4Wl"
          target="_blank"
          >Chemical Storage Safety (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/9kK3sW1uu9U?si=Nc9ghap1S8ti5wgi"
          target="_blank"
          >Store Household Chemicals Safely (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12704">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      <b>Chemistry and First Aid.</b> After successfully completing requirement
      1, do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12704 mb-requirement-id-12705">
        (a) Discuss with your counselor why you think soap and alcohol are used
        to clean cuts and scrapes. Discuss how you could test your hypotheses
        with your counselor. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7KKkElpyKQ" target="_blank"
          >Soap and Hand Sanitizers vs Viruses and Bacteria (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12704 mb-requirement-id-12706">
        (b) Coat your hands with a mixture of cooking oil and a nontoxic powder,
        such as sand or cocoa. Wash your hands with water and observe what
        happens. Coat your hands again, then wash with soap and water. Discuss
        the differences with your counselor. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/Jx5BgbIkXEs" target="_blank"
          >How Does Soap Work? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12704 mb-requirement-id-12707">
        (c) Perform an experiment to demonstrate how rubbing alcohol affects
        microbial growth using baker's yeast. Discuss the results with your
        counselor. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/Jx5BgbIkXEs" target="_blank"
          >Watching How Alcohol Kills Viruses and Bacteria Under a Microscope
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12724">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      <b>Chemistry and Cooking.</b> After successfully completing requirement 1,
      do EACH of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12724 mb-requirement-id-12726">
        (a) Perform a Maillard, or browning, reaction. Discuss with your
        counselor whether a physical or chemical change has occurred, and what
        happened to molecules in the food during the cooking process. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/rs1JLYXROVU" target="_blank"
          >The Maillard Reaction (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/tOkCgAwhh9U" target="_blank"
          >Why Pizza Tastes So Good (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5lKzZc_OO7U" target="_blank"
          >Understanding the Maillard Reaction (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12724 mb-requirement-id-12727">
        (b) Prepare and use red cabbage indicator to measure the pH of five
        common household liquids, including water. Discuss your observations
        with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/4AElaDIhMyA?si=Xy70e7RL3auxEy8F"
          target="_blank"
          >Why Is Red Cabbage a pH Indicator (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/hPcRylO4lQM?si=tMGhB4e9QtPvN3Xx"
          target="_blank"
          >pH Indicator Made From Red Cabbage (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.compoundchem.com/2017/05/18/red-cabbage/"
          target="_blank"
          >Red Cabbage Indicator Infographic (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12708">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      <b>Chemistry and Camping.</b> After successfully completing requirement 1,
      do TWO of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12708 mb-requirement-id-12709">
        (a) Design and conduct an experiment to compare at least two different
        types of waterproofing. Discuss with your counselor which one you would
        prefer to use on your tent and which one you would prefer to use on your
        boots, and why. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/s3fDbnfolCM" target="_blank"
          >Transforming Paper into a Waterproof Marvel (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/y83uXupu5tY" target="_blank"
          >Waterproofing Fabrics (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/UlHfbltn6hI" target="_blank"
          >Waterproofing Tent Seams (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12708 mb-requirement-id-12710">
        (b) Describe the four classes of fires, and the four classes of fire
        extinguishers. Discuss with your counselor how sand, baking soda, and
        the four classes of extinguishers work to put out fires. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B8PrA_AOa6w" target="_blank"
          >Four Classes of Fires (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Epa_2mCi4lw" target="_blank"
          >Four Types of Fires (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12708 mb-requirement-id-12711">
        (c) Under your counselor's supervision and/or the supervision of a
        knowledgeable adult approved in advance by your counselor, conduct flame
        tests of at least five elements using a kitchen or propane torch.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7hC-KyFraCQ" target="_blank"
          >Metal Flame Test (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12708 mb-requirement-id-12728">
        (d) Under your counselor's supervision and/or the supervision of a
        knowledgeable adult approved in advance by your counselor, synthesize
        nylon (may be from a kit). <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NQpTQFGKRN8" target="_blank"
          >Making Nylon (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
